This is the slight link by which the controversy is connected with the subject of the chapter3 and here comes the tug of war between Universalists and Nominalists. Wyclif urges that if we say, “A certain man has stolen something, and heis a thief‚³² we may very well be ignorant of the particular lte who has committed the theft. He therefore does not stand, as Nominalists would have it, for the individual himself, but for the Universal “A certain man who has stolen this or that''. Nominalists say they know this disjunctively: it is either A or B or C, &c. But this is an idle quibble: to know thus disjunctively is not to know (p. 26, l. 31 to end3 p. 27, I. 1 to 20).

Now all this looks to modern readers —- and since they are modern, they must of course be in the right — very much like mere loss of time and trouble; useless expenditure of brain-work. To the Oxford wranglers of those days, on the contrary, it must have been full of actuality and interest: for it was the very central point round which the battle raged, and Wyclif's unet-ring acumen, in thus coming to the point at once, is greatly to be admired‚ if we can for an instant forget our superiority as “moderns’'. The Nominalists ssatly denied the existence of anything but the concrete. For them, a universal name was in itself a mere “flatus voeis³’, according to Ockam's famous expression; it had no meaning except when applied to its singulars. They therefore could not possibly admit that the pronoun lte (or indeed any pronoun3 who or which, for instance) stood for a universal Thing, nor even merely for the words which it replaced (which would still give universality of a certain kind). It had to stand for a singular object, an individual man or being. “But then,³’ said the Universalists, “if it stands for only one individual, you must know who lte is, when you say, He is a· tlzief, as usual in such sentences. If you do not know, and deny that it stands for somebody in general, the sentence becomes a jumble of words, without any mean- ing³'. We are not here concerned in the Nominalist⁷s reply, which must have been rather shuffling and embarrassed, at least for those of the extreme school os Ockam.
